{"title_page": "NSW Rail Museum", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates | date=August 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English | date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name                = NSW Rail Museum\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| logo                = the New South Wales Rail Transport Museum.jpg\n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Buxton Station Locomotive.jpg\n| image_upright       = 1.4\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = [[New South Wales Z27 class locomotive|2705]] at [[Buxton railway station, New South Wales|Buxton station]] operating a  [[Picton - Mittagong loop railway line]] service\n| map_type            = New South Wales\n| map_relief          = 1\n| map_size            = 270\n| map_caption         = Location in [[New South Wales]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|-34.2064|150.5695|type:landmark_region:AU-NSW|display=title,inline|format=dms}}<!-- {{Coord}} -->\n| former_name         = {{bulleted list|New South Wales Rail Transport Museum|Trainworks}}\n| established         = {{start date|1962|df=y}}<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| location            = 10 Barbour Road, [[Thirlmere, New South Wales|Thirlmere]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| type                = [[Railway museum]]\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = \n| visitors            = \n| founder             = \n| executive_director  = \n| leader_type         = \n| leader              = \n| director            = \n| president           = \n| ceo                 = \n| chairperson         = \n| curator             = \n| architect           = \n| historian           = \n| owner               = \n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = On site\n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = {{URL|www.nswrailmuseum.com.au}}\n| embedded            = \n}}\n\nThe '''NSW Rail Museum''' is the main [[railway museum]] in [[New South Wales]], Australia. A division of [[Transport Heritage NSW]], it was previously known as the '''New South Wales Rail Transport Museum''' (NSWRTM) and '''Trainworks'''.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Bennett, David | title=Introducing the NSW Rail Museum Brand | magazine=[[Roundhouse (periodical)|Roundhouse]] |volume=54 | issue=1| date=January 2017}}</ref>\n\nTransport Heritage NSW has divisions located in [[Thirlmere, New South Wales]], where the NSW Rail Museum is dedicated to displaying [[locomotives]], [[Passenger car (rail)|passenger cars]], and [[Goods wagon#Types of goods wagon|freight]] [[rolling stock]] formerly operated by the [[New South Wales Government Railways]] (NSWGR) and various private operators.  The [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]] division is located at the [[Valley Heights Locomotive Depot Heritage Museum]]. \n\n* At Thirlmere, the NSW Rail Museum operates steam heritage trains on the [[Picton - Mittagong loop railway line|Picton \u2013 Mittagong railway line]] between [[Picton railway station, New South Wales|Picton]], Thirlmere and [[Buxton railway station, New South Wales|Buxton]].  It also hosts the Thirlmere Festival of Steam in March each year.\n* In addition to this, Transport Heritage NSW regularly operates mainline tours under the ''NSW Rail Museum'' branding.  These can consist of day or extended tours, usually over a weekend.\n* At Valley Heights, the co-located Valley Heights Steam Tramway runs an 1890s steam tram and trailer, and a Stephenson loco 0-6-0 CPC2 (built in 1899) with open ended carriage over track in the former roundhouse and associated access tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobluemountains.net.au/locodepot/tram/exhibits_tram103a.shtml|title=Tram 103a at Valley Heights Steam Tramway |accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:3801 at Newcastle.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|[[3801]] at [[Newcastle railway station, New South Wales|Newcastle]] preparing to head south with a ''[[Newcastle Flyer]]'' special in 2007]]\nThe NSWRTM was established in October 1962 with 62 members. A survey of potential sites around Sydney found [[Enfield Locomotive Depot]] to be the most suitable and in 1963 a successful submission was made to the Department of Railways. Under the arrangement the department would retain ownership of the locomotives and rolling stock and responsibility for their maintenance. As Enfield depot was still active, exhibits were sent to Enfield for storage but not able to be accessed. In 1967 the Department made an area adjacent to [[Petersham railway station|Petersham station]] available to the museum. The first locomotives outshopped were [[New South Wales C35 class locomotive|3526]] and [[New South Wales C36 class locomotive|3609]] painted blue and green.<ref name=RoundhouseJan94>\"The New South Wales Rail Transport Museum; The First Thirty Years\" ''[[Roundhouse (periodical)|Roundhouse]]'' January 1994; page 4</ref>\n\nIn July 1969 the NSWRTM was able to move into Enfield Roundhouse Number 3 with all exhibits transferred by September. In 1970 the museum was able to relocate into the larger Roundhouse Number 1, allowing the majority of the collection to be stored undercover. In October 1972 the display at Enfield was officially opened by Commissioner for Railways, Neil McCusker.<ref name=RoundhouseJan94/><ref name=aboutus>{{cite web| url=http://www.nswrtm.org/aboutus.html| title=About The NSW Rail Transport Museum| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222030353/http://www.nswrtm.org/aboutus.html| archivedate=22 February 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:3820Thirlmere1991.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[3820]] as a static exhibit circa 1991]]\n[[File:Silvercom.jpg|thumb|right|Preserved [[Silver City Comet|Silver City Comet power car DP104]]]]\nThe NSWRTM had always maintained a good relationship with the Department of Railways, but in 1973 it was replaced by the [[Public Transport Commission]]. The PTC under Commissioner Philip Shirley decided it wanted all steam locomotives, including those owned by preservation organisations, off the network with [[3820]] operating the NSWRTM's last tour to [[Taree railway station|Taree]] in 1974. The PTC also decided it wanted nothing to do with maintaining the NSWRTM's collection and handed over the exhibits to the museum under a Deed of Gift.<ref name=RoundhouseJan94/>\n\nThe PTC also wanted to demolish the Enfield roundhouses to make way for a container terminal and offered the museum a site at [[Thirlmere, New South Wales|Thirlmere]] on the then lightly used [[Picton - Mittagong loop railway line|Picton \u2013 Mittagong loop line]].<ref name=RoundhouseJan94/> Site clearing began in late 1974 and works were sufficiently advanced for the transfer of stock to begin in June 1975.  While some trains were hauled by diesel locomotives, most were worked by the museum's own steam locomotives.<ref name=RoundhouseJul76>\"Museum on the Move\" ''Roundhouse'' July 1976 page 5</ref>\n\nThe NSWRTM opened at its current location in on 1 June 1976.<ref>{{cite web | last=Geier| first=Matthew| title=New South Wales Rail Transport Museum| url=http://www.sleeper.apana.org.au/railway/nswrtm.html| accessdate=31 January 2012| year=1996}}</ref>  Services on the loop line between Thirlmere and Buxton began on 13 June 1976.<ref name=RoundhouseJul76/>  Initially uncovered, the first section of roofing was completed in 1979.  It was over a decade before the whole site was covered.\n\nThe PTC relaxed its ban on main line steam in October 1976. [[3801]] returned to the main line.  By the early 1980s it was operating enthusiast journeys on a regular basis including a monthly service from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney Central]] to Thirlmere.<ref name=RoundhouseJan94/>\n\nIn 1984 the NSWRTM became a founding member of the [[3801 Limited]] managerial board that was created to oversee the operation of the locomotive [[3801]].  The famous British railway locomotive [[LNER Class A3 4472 Flying Scotsman|4472 ''Flying Scotsman'']] visited Thirlmere in March 1989 as part of its tour around Australia.<ref>\"Gala Day 1989\" ''Roundhouse'' April 1989 page 28</ref>\n\nIn 1993 the museum concluded a lease for the {{convert|14|km|adj=on}} [[Picton - Mittagong loop railway line|Picton \u2013 Buxton railway line]] following its closure by the [[State Rail Authority]].<ref>\"Rail Transport Museum Set to Lease Loop Line\" ''[[Railway Digest]]'' August 1993 page 316</ref>\n\nThe NSWRTM was removed as a board member of [[3801 Limited]] in November 2006 after the 20-year lease of [[3801]] was not renewed.  The locomotive was returned to the NSWRTM.<ref>[http://www.nswrtm.org/3801/documents/06-02-00-RTMmail.pdf 3801 Limited] ''RTM Mail'' February 2006</ref>\n\n==Redevelopment==\nIn 2006 the [[Government of New South Wales]] endorsed the Sustainable Rail Heritage Asset Management Strategy to ensure the collection of the State\u2019s rail heritage assets are maintained and conserved by dedicated volunteers and shared with the public for current and future generations to appreciate and enjoy. In 2007 [[RailCorp]]\u2019s Office of Rail Heritage commissioned the development of a concept design for the NSWRTM\u2019s upgrade. This saw ownership in the NSWRTM vested in Trainworks Limited, a 100% subsidiary of RailCorp.<ref>[http://www.railcorp.info/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/10446/RailCorp_Annual_Report_2010-2011.pdf Annual Report 2010/11] RailCorp 30 June 2011</ref>\n\nA major redevelopment saw the locomotive depot relocated to a roundhouse built at the southern end of the site opening in November 2009.<ref>[http://www.trainworks.com.au/about_us_upgrade_evolution Upgrade Evolution] Trainworks</ref>  To create room for stage two of the development of the museum, some of the exhibits were moved to [[Broadmeadow Locomotive Depot|Broadmeadow]] and [[Goulburn Rail Heritage Centre|Goulburn]] in 2009. Work on stage two began in December 2009, which included demolition of the existing locomotive maintenance building, construction of a new major exhibits building and other works. The New South Wales Rail Transport Museum re-opened in April 2011.<ref>{{cite web | title=Museum Development Upgrade Information| url=http://www.nswrtm.org/news/museum_development.html| publisher=NSW Rail Transport Museum| accessdate=9 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\nThe museum has over 2,300 members, including an active volunteer workforce of over 400 and a small number of full-time staff.<ref name=aboutus/> It is administered by a voluntary Board and a Management Committee. The museum is accredited as a rail operator under the NSW Rail Safety Act 2002 meaning it has network access rights on the NSW main line rail network. It also has accreditation to operate in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref>[http://www.transportsafety.vic.gov.au/rail-safety/accreditation/accredited-rail-operators Accredited Rail Operators] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409155919/http://www.transportsafety.vic.gov.au/rail-safety/accreditation/accredited-rail-operators |date=9 April 2013 }} Transport Safety Victoria</ref>\n\n==Amalgamation==\nIn May 2013, the [[Minister for Transport (New South Wales)|Minister for Transport]] announced [[Transport Heritage NSW]], a new not-for-profit company, would be established to manage rail heritage in NSW following an independent review of rail heritage commissioned by the NSW Government. THNSW have responsibility for the rebranded NSW Rail Museum and the Valley Heights site\n\nAll assets were transferred to THNSW after the merge\n\nShortly after the merge Trainworks was rebranded to the NSW Rail Museum\n\n<br />\n\n==Publications==\n* [[Roundhouse (periodical)|''Roundhouse'' (periodical)]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|New South Wales|Railways}}\n* [[List of transport museums]]\n* [[NSWGR steam locomotive classification]]\n* [[Rail Paybus FP1]]\n* [[Rail transport in New South Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Trainworks Railway Museum}}\n* [https://www.nswrailmuseum.com.au/ NSW Rail Museum website]\n* [https://www.transportheritagensw.com.au/ Transport Heritage NSW website]\n* [http://valleyheightsrailmuseum.info/ Valley Heights Locomotive Depot Heritage Museum]\n* [http://www.australiansteam.com/nswgrframe.htm NSW Preserved Steam Locomotives]\n\n{{Railway lines in New South Wales|state=collapsed}}\n[[Category:Railway museums in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Thirlmere, New South Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates | date=August 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English | date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name                = NSW Rail Museum\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| logo                = the New South Wales Rail Transport Museum.jpg\n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Buxton Station Locomotive.jpg\n| image_upright       = 1.4\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = [[New South Wales Z27 class locomotive|2705]] at [[Buxton railway station, New South Wales|Buxton station]] operating a  [[Picton - Mittagong loop railway line]] service\n| map_type            = New South Wales\n| map_relief          = 1\n| map_size            = 270\n| map_caption         = Location in [[New South Wales]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|-34.2064|150.5695|type:landmark_region:AU-NSW|display=title,inline|format=dms}}<!-- {{Coord}} -->\n| former_name         = {{bulleted list|New South Wales Rail Transport Museum|Trainworks}}\n| established         = {{start date|1962|df=y}}<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| location            = 10 Barbour Road, [[Thirlmere, New South Wales|Thirlmere]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| type                = [[Railway museum]]\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = \n| visitors            = \n| founder             = \n| executive_director  = \n| leader_type         = \n| leader              = \n| director            = \n| president           = \n| ceo                 = \n| chairperson         = \n| curator             = \n| architect           = \n| historian           = \n| owner               = \n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = On site\n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = {{URL|www.nswrailmuseum.com.au}}\n| embedded            = \n}}\n\nThe '''NSW Rail Museum''' is the main [[railway museum]] in [[New South Wales]], Australia. A division of [[Transport Heritage NSW]], it was previously known as the '''New South Wales Rail Transport Museum''' (NSWRTM) and '''Trainworks'''.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Bennett, David | title=Introducing the NSW Rail Museum Brand | magazine=[[Roundhouse (periodical)|Roundhouse]] |volume=54 | issue=1| date=January 2017}}</ref>\n\nTransport Heritage NSW has divisions located in [[Thirlmere, New South Wales]], where the NSW Rail Museum is dedicated to displaying [[locomotives]], [[Passenger car (rail)|passenger cars]], and [[Goods wagon#Types of goods wagon|freight]] [[rolling stock]] formerly operated by the [[New South Wales Government Railways]] (NSWGR) and various private operators.  The [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]] division is located at the [[Valley Heights Locomotive Depot Heritage Museum]]. The collection features [[Steam locomotive|steam]], [[Diesel locomotive|diesel]] and [[electric locomotive]]s and other rolling stock.  A large proportion of the collection is owned by [[Transport for New South Wales]].\n\n* At Thirlmere, the NSW Rail Museum operates steam heritage trains on the [[Picton - Mittagong loop railway line|Picton \u2013 Mittagong railway line]] between [[Picton railway station, New South Wales|Picton]], Thirlmere and [[Buxton railway station, New South Wales|Buxton]].  It also hosts the Thirlmere Festival of Steam in March each year.\n* In addition to this, Transport Heritage NSW regularly operates mainline tours under the ''NSW Rail Museum'' branding.  These can consist of day or extended tours, usually over a weekend.\n* At Valley Heights, the co-located Valley Heights Steam Tramway runs an 1890s steam tram and trailer, and a Stephenson loco 0-6-0 CPC2 (built in 1899) with open ended carriage over track in the former roundhouse and associated access tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobluemountains.net.au/locodepot/tram/exhibits_tram103a.shtml|title=Tram 103a at Valley Heights Steam Tramway |accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:3801 at Newcastle.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|[[3801]] at [[Newcastle railway station, New South Wales|Newcastle]] preparing to head south with a ''[[Newcastle Flyer]]'' special in 2007]]\nThe NSWRTM was established in October 1962 with 62 members. A survey of potential sites around Sydney found [[Enfield Locomotive Depot]] to be the most suitable and in 1963 a successful submission was made to the Department of Railways. Under the arrangement the department would retain ownership of the locomotives and rolling stock and responsibility for their maintenance. As Enfield depot was still active, exhibits were sent to Enfield for storage but not able to be accessed. In 1967 the Department made an area adjacent to [[Petersham railway station|Petersham station]] available to the museum. The first locomotives outshopped were [[New South Wales C35 class locomotive|3526]] and [[New South Wales C36 class locomotive|3609]] painted blue and green.<ref name=RoundhouseJan94>\"The New South Wales Rail Transport Museum; The First Thirty Years\" ''[[Roundhouse (periodical)|Roundhouse]]'' January 1994; page 4</ref>\n\nIn July 1969 the NSWRTM was able to move into Enfield Roundhouse Number 3 with all exhibits transferred by September. In 1970 the museum was able to relocate into the larger Roundhouse Number 1, allowing the majority of the collection to be stored undercover. In October 1972 the display at Enfield was officially opened by Commissioner for Railways, Neil McCusker.<ref name=RoundhouseJan94/><ref name=aboutus>{{cite web| url=http://www.nswrtm.org/aboutus.html| title=About The NSW Rail Transport Museum| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222030353/http://www.nswrtm.org/aboutus.html| archivedate=22 February 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:3820Thirlmere1991.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[3820]] as a static exhibit circa 1991]]\n[[File:Silvercom.jpg|thumb|right|Preserved [[Silver City Comet|Silver City Comet power car DP104]]]]\nThe NSWRTM had always maintained a good relationship with the Department of Railways, but in 1973 it was replaced by the [[Public Transport Commission]]. The PTC under Commissioner Philip Shirley decided it wanted all steam locomotives, including those owned by preservation organisations, off the network with [[3820]] operating the NSWRTM's last tour to [[Taree railway station|Taree]] in 1974. The PTC also decided it wanted nothing to do with maintaining the NSWRTM's collection and handed over the exhibits to the museum under a Deed of Gift.<ref name=RoundhouseJan94/>\n\nThe PTC also wanted to demolish the Enfield roundhouses to make way for a container terminal and offered the museum a site at [[Thirlmere, New South Wales|Thirlmere]] on the then lightly used [[Picton - Mittagong loop railway line|Picton \u2013 Mittagong loop line]].<ref name=RoundhouseJan94/> Site clearing began in late 1974 and works were sufficiently advanced for the transfer of stock to begin in June 1975.  While some trains were hauled by diesel locomotives, most were worked by the museum's own steam locomotives.<ref name=RoundhouseJul76>\"Museum on the Move\" ''Roundhouse'' July 1976 page 5</ref>\n\nThe NSWRTM opened at its current location in on 1 June 1976.<ref>{{cite web | last=Geier| first=Matthew| title=New South Wales Rail Transport Museum| url=http://www.sleeper.apana.org.au/railway/nswrtm.html| accessdate=31 January 2012| year=1996}}</ref>  Services on the loop line between Thirlmere and Buxton began on 13 June 1976.<ref name=RoundhouseJul76/>  Initially uncovered, the first section of roofing was completed in 1979.  It was over a decade before the whole site was covered.\n\nThe PTC relaxed its ban on main line steam in October 1976. [[3801]] returned to the main line.  By the early 1980s it was operating enthusiast journeys on a regular basis including a monthly service from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney Central]] to Thirlmere.<ref name=RoundhouseJan94/>\n\nIn 1984 the NSWRTM became a founding member of the [[3801 Limited]] managerial board that was created to oversee the operation of the locomotive [[3801]].  The famous British railway locomotive [[LNER Class A3 4472 Flying Scotsman|4472 ''Flying Scotsman'']] visited Thirlmere in March 1989 as part of its tour around Australia.<ref>\"Gala Day 1989\" ''Roundhouse'' April 1989 page 28</ref>\n\nIn 1993 the museum concluded a lease for the {{convert|14|km|adj=on}} [[Picton - Mittagong loop railway line|Picton \u2013 Buxton railway line]] following its closure by the [[State Rail Authority]].<ref>\"Rail Transport Museum Set to Lease Loop Line\" ''[[Railway Digest]]'' August 1993 page 316</ref>\n\nThe NSWRTM was removed as a board member of [[3801 Limited]] in November 2006 after the 20-year lease of [[3801]] was not renewed.  The locomotive was returned to the NSWRTM.<ref>[http://www.nswrtm.org/3801/documents/06-02-00-RTMmail.pdf 3801 Limited] ''RTM Mail'' February 2006</ref>\n\n==Redevelopment==\nIn 2006 the [[Government of New South Wales]] endorsed the Sustainable Rail Heritage Asset Management Strategy to ensure the collection of the State\u2019s rail heritage assets are maintained and conserved by dedicated volunteers and shared with the public for current and future generations to appreciate and enjoy. In 2007 [[RailCorp]]\u2019s Office of Rail Heritage commissioned the development of a concept design for the NSWRTM\u2019s upgrade. This saw ownership in the NSWRTM vested in Trainworks Limited, a 100% subsidiary of RailCorp.<ref>[http://www.railcorp.info/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/10446/RailCorp_Annual_Report_2010-2011.pdf Annual Report 2010/11] RailCorp 30 June 2011</ref>\n\nA major redevelopment saw the locomotive depot relocated to a roundhouse built at the southern end of the site opening in November 2009.<ref>[http://www.trainworks.com.au/about_us_upgrade_evolution Upgrade Evolution] Trainworks</ref>  To create room for stage two of the development of the museum, some of the exhibits were moved to [[Broadmeadow Locomotive Depot|Broadmeadow]] and [[Goulburn Rail Heritage Centre|Goulburn]] in 2009. Work on stage two began in December 2009, which included demolition of the existing locomotive maintenance building, construction of a new major exhibits building and other works. The New South Wales Rail Transport Museum re-opened in April 2011.<ref>{{cite web | title=Museum Development Upgrade Information| url=http://www.nswrtm.org/news/museum_development.html| publisher=NSW Rail Transport Museum| accessdate=9 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\nThe museum has over 2,300 members, including an active volunteer workforce of over 400 and a small number of full-time staff.<ref name=aboutus/> It is administered by a voluntary Board and a Management Committee. The museum is accredited as a rail operator under the NSW Rail Safety Act 2002 meaning it has network access rights on the NSW main line rail network. It also has accreditation to operate in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref>[http://www.transportsafety.vic.gov.au/rail-safety/accreditation/accredited-rail-operators Accredited Rail Operators] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409155919/http://www.transportsafety.vic.gov.au/rail-safety/accreditation/accredited-rail-operators |date=9 April 2013 }} Transport Safety Victoria</ref>\n\n==Amalgamation==\nIn May 2013, the [[Minister for Transport (New South Wales)|Minister for Transport]] announced [[Transport Heritage NSW]], a new not-for-profit company, would be established to manage rail heritage in NSW following an independent review of rail heritage commissioned by the NSW Government. The new company will take responsibility for the New South Wales Rail Transport Museum, Trainworks and [[RailCorp]]'s Office of Rail Heritage.<ref>[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/fixing-trains-fresh-start-rail-heritage Fixing the trains: A fresh start for Rail Heritage] Transport for NSW 17 May 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/publications/0513-transport-heritage-report-web-final.pdf Rail Heritage Review - All Aboard! A fresh start for Transport Heritage in NSW] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217055220/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/publications/0513-transport-heritage-report-web-final.pdf |date=17 December 2013 }} Transport for NSW 17 May 2013</ref>\n\n==Museum exhibits==\nThe Museum has an extensive collection of railway locomotives, carriages, wagons and other railway equipment from both the NSWGR and privately operated railways:\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"width: 100%; font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"9\" bgcolor=\"#FFB300\" | Steam Locomotives\n|-\n!No!!Description!!Manufacturer!!Year!!Location!!Status!!Ref\n|--style=\"background:#E5E5FF\"\n| [[New South Wales X10 class locomotive|1021]]||[[0-4-0T]] saddle tank||[[Manning Wardle]]||1896||[[Thirlmere, New South Wales|Thirlmere]]||static exhibit||[http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4807204 Locomotive, Steam 1021]\n|-\n|[[New South Wales X10 class locomotive|1033]]||[[2-4-0T]] passenger tank||[[Beyer, Peacock and Company]]||1885||[[Thirlmere, 